The album kicks off with "[Talking Bout My Baby](/Talkin%27_bout_My_Baby)," a track that immediately sets the tone with its soulful groove, a testament to Cook's ability to blend diverse influences. This segues into "[Star 69](/Star_69_(Fatboy_Slim_song))," a track infamous for its explicit language and undeniable energy, becoming one of the album's defining, and in some circles, most controversial, anthems. "[Sunset (Bird of Prey)](/Sunset_(Bird_of_Prey))" showcases a more atmospheric side, cleverly incorporating samples that elevate its sonic landscape.

"Love Life," featuring the distinctive rasp of [Macy Gray](/Macy_Gray), offers a moment of vocal warmth and introspection amidst the beats, while "[Ya Mama](/Song_for_Shelter_/_Ya_Mama)" dives headfirst back into the raw, infectious funk that [Fatboy Slim](/Fatboy_Slim) is renowned for. "Mad Flava" serves as a pure, unadulterated instrumental showcase of Cook's production prowess, leading into "[Retox](/Retox_(song))", another collaboration with [Ashley Slater](/Ashley_Slater) that injects further vocal texture and groove.

Perhaps the most recognizable track, "[Weapon of Choice](/Weapon_of_Choice_(song))," featuring the legendary [Bootsy Collins](/Bootsy_Collins), is a masterclass in funk-infused [electronic music](/Electronic_music). Its iconic music video, starring [Christopher Walken](/Christopher_Walken), propelled it into the cultural zeitgeist, proving that sometimes, even dance music can achieve mainstream, critically acclaimed artistry. "[Drop the Hate](/Drop_the_Hate)" provides a darker, more intense rhythm, while "[Demons](/Demons_(Fatboy_Slim_song))," with [Macy Gray](/Macy_Gray) returning, offers a soulful, almost gospel-tinged narrative. The album concludes with the sprawling "[Song for Shelter](/Song_for_Shelter_/_Ya_Mama)," featuring [Roland Clark](/Roland_Clark_(DJ)) and [Roger Sanchez](/Roger_Sanchez), which includes a [hidden track](/Hidden_track)—a reprise of "Talking 'bout My Baby"—a subtle nod to the album's opening, bringing the journey full circle, or perhaps just leaving a lingering echo for those patient enough to wait.

